Initial observations¶

1. Data introduction.¶

  • This data set is taken from Kaggle from the following URL: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/devsubhash/fitness-trackers-products-ecommerce

  • Data collected from Flipkart on the sales, specifications and ratings of 565 fitness wearables in India market. Web-scraping techniques were used to gather the data.

  • Attributes summary:

    • Brand Name: This indicates the manufacturer of the product (fitness tracker)
    • Device Type: This has two categories- FitnessBand and Smartwatch
    • Model Name: This indicates the variant/Product Name
    • Color: This includes the color of the Strap/Body of the fitness tracker
    • Selling Price: This column has the Selling Price or the Discounted Price of the fitness tracker
    • Original Price: This includes the Original Price of the product from the manufacturer.
    • Display: This categorical variable shows the type of display for the fitness tracker. eg: AMOLED, LCD,OLED, etc.
    • Rating (Out of 5): Average customer ratings on a scale of 5.
    • Strap Material: Details of the material used for the strap of the fitness tracker.
    • Average Battery Life (in days): Quoted average battery life from the manufacturer based on the individual product pages. (It is not the scraped data)
    • Reviews: count of product reviews received.

Brief review¶

  • Dataset contains a few duplicated values.
  • The Reviews columns seems to be incredibly insufficient, thus will be dropped. Otherwise, the data is relatively clean.
  • The Selling Price and Original Price is being treated as columns with Object dypes, which must be convert to int datatype.
  • Rating would likely be one of our major focus for basing our customer behavioral analysis.

Drawbacks¶

  • Market range is not in the Australian market. Since this data was scraped from Flipkart India.
  • The actual sales of each products are not available, which makes sense given the context of our data. However, this leaves the quality of our analysis to be left desirable as Ratings do not necessary reflect the sales potential of the product
  • Too many missing values in the Reviews column. Original and Selling Prices are in the wrong format.

2. Analysis Directions¶

  • Possible questions to be answered:

    • Is there any notable trend on how ratings are given?
    • Are we able to find correlation between discounts/screen type/strap material/battery life vs others?
    • How can our analysis be helpful for Redback Operations?

  • After taking a look through our data, our goals for this analysis could be towards the following:

    • Highlighting the overall distrubtion of brands in the market.
    • Visualizing ratings of brands, and the different types of devices.
    • Finding the correlations between notable attributes of the wearbles.

5. Recommendations¶

  • We should be looking at the development of Smartwatches as the form factor seems to be well-received and is able to provide more functionality to users.

  • Battery life shows clear indication towards user's judgement for the products - suggesting that

  • Screen type is also an important to taken in mind of, the two most preferred choices are OLED Retina and AMOLED displays. On the other hand, we should avoid using TFT-LCD displays as it shown a significant difference of ratings between others.

  • Entry-level devices seem to be more approachable for users.
